node.text:
The #OneOceanSeries continues on IGTV & Youtube, watch others, and read the book and take the only course that this info builds on @OceanRamsey or via links in her bio on her website: OceanRamsey.Org

I’ve been working with sharks for well over 20 years around the world and I want people to have the amazing experience and connection felt when they get to go diving with them which is part of the reason @OcenaRamsey and I co-founded @Oneoceandiving and its many divisions because we know it will inspire conservation and respect is grown through a deeper understanding from knowledge shared.  

It is my hope that sharing this information will help people to be safer while enjoying time with sharks but we want to give a strong disclaimer that people should not attempt to reproduce scenes from this series, this is for emergency reference and awareness only.  The JAWSOME safety guides at @oneoceanDiving go through the most extensive and strenuous in-depth behavioral and applied training and if you’re ever going diving purposefully with sharks please be respectful and go with an extensively experienced professional guide who works with sharks in-water full time. 

@OneOceanDiving in unfortunatly losing one of its most amazing lady shark scientists because her husband is going to teach at a university on the mainland (congrats,) so we are hiring people with a deep passion for shark and marine conservation.  Must also already have a PADI divemaster certification or PADI freedive instructor cert, GRIT, and ideally with a marine science or related degree.   Apply by emailing the @OneoceanDiving office.

Disclaimer this sub-series is more than 4 parts, the 1st part of the series was released in 2 parts on @OceanRamsey’s IG and Part 3 will be on hers next.  We want to help people and sharks to coexist as safely and respectfully as possible and sometime that means giving them their space back and exiting the water, even if you’re extremely experienced working around them. We generally only start to share this information with professional shark safety diver guides once they’ve already been working with sharks on a daily basis for an extended period of time, only those who have the water skill required to quickly and efficiently move themselves in the water and adapt to a rapid approach and are trained to look in all directions continuously to see an approach or issue before it becomes a serious issue. As a photographer and videographer I want to get a stable shot but I won’t compromise safety to get that shot, it’s not worth disrespecting the sharks and risking their reputation so if I need to be stable then I have @Oceanramsey of one of the professional shark safety divers we’ve trained watch my back. 

I make deterring a large shark look easier than it is because I’ve done it a lot in many places around the world with many species and I’ve worked in the water daily for more than two decades specifically for water safety and mostly always focused around sharks. 

So, please be respectful of them and stay safe, don’t become complacent or assume every approach or shark species or location will be the same, it won’t. 

Special mahalo nui loa (thank you so much) to my love @OceanRamsey for filming me, being my safety, and demonstrating many of the techniques I talk about. Also special thank you to our amazing editor @Jarebutler for your incredible work. 

Learn more by taking @OceanRamsey’s online course, watching the rest of this free series, and check out Ocean’s book “What you should know about sharks” Link on my website JuanSharks.Com

node.text:
Usually, I think we would be quiet about this gorgeous tiger shark hope spot, but people need to know how unique this place is to preserve and protect the harmony the community has with the ocean and the marine life surrounding the island. The only thing that is out of balance is what is happening on land with plastic pollution. While I was there, I saw two boats full of water bottles come in and only one boat leaving with the trash. The infrastructure can’t keep up with the demand for freshwater. The easy solution is water filters for everyone, and they can
almost cut their plastic pollution in half, and the growing mountain of trash can be eliminated. If your planning to come to experience the dives with the tiger sharks here in Fuvahmulah or want to help protect the sharks and the ecosystem here, please donate to the link in the bio  @savetheseaturtleinternational donations are tax delectable, and @naturefriendsofmaldives along with @pelagicdivefuvahmulah will be distributing them on the island. A huge Mahalos and thanks to some of the 1st sponsors to donate units @nakaialimatharesort @hurawalhi @aristonmaldives @aristondive @btwaves @mikecoots @pelagicdivefuvahmulah #preservingthebeauty #protecttheocean #helpsavesharks #savethereef #noplasticwaterbottles #reuse #sustianable #oceanconservation #tigersharks #tigerharkisland #maldives

Hawaii is introducing bills to help stop this and give Mano’ the protect they need and deserve.  Please help by supporting links in video and being a conscious consumer. I was super stoked to be part of @envoyfilm, which exposes the shark culling happening in Australia. In 2014 we helped expose the trialed shark cull in Western Australia, and the government ended the program after three months.

Unfortunately on the other side of Australia, in Queensland and New South Wales, the cull continues. It's been running since 1937, for 83 years. 

International cinema and streaming releases are coming in early 2021, but for now, anyone in Australia can see it in cinemas on the big screen:

node.text:
Words by @alanarblanchard
・・・
PLEASE READ!! As some of you might know I was in the water when my best friend got her arm bite off by a tiger shark. For many years after (especially after having a kid) I would think about the attack and even dream about sharks trying to get me. I developed a fear of sharks and every time I surfed I would get this crazy hit of  anxiety  that I would have to talk myself out of. Since surfing and being in the water is my life Iv been trying to work on this and educate myself on sharks and there behavior. Then almost 17 years later  a tiger shark named Riley came and said hello while diving with @oceanramsey and @juansharks I never thought I would be swimming with something I feared for so long. Riley did about 4 passes by us and I was able to dive down and make eye contact, it was beautiful and I’ll alway remember it. I had tears of joy instead of this fear I thought I would of have. It was peaceful and it was like he was telling me something..... they are not the thing we need to fear. I know this can be hard to wrap your head around but shark attacks are very rare and they don’t see us as food. All I know is we need to save these amazing creatures. We need them more then they need us. If you guys want more info please go to @oceanramsey and @juansharks they are experts in all things sharks. #helpsavesharks #savethesharks NO #sharkfinsoup #learnaboutsharks 🎥 @jaketaiwan4 and @juansharks 

So stoked we could make this dive happen with you and  @jackfreestone  @anthony_walsh_  looking forward to more. 🙏🏼🤙🏽💙🦈

node.text: I just wanted to share some information that I thought would help surfers and swimmers avoid adverse interactions with sharks during the Fall months.  This time of year we have large female tiger sharks coming into shallow waters to pup and potentially mate.  During the last part of a tiger shark pregnancy, they stop feeding. It is theorized that this happens so they avoid potentially eating other sharks pups in the same area.  Tiger sharks timing for this coincides with the arrival of humpback whales pupping as well which for tiger sharks means a easy meal at the time they need it the most, also other prey items would be fledging birds and sea turtles feeding at the shoreline.  Simple things like avoiding splashing like a hurt injured animal, avoid surfboards that outline the shape of a turtle, never sit waiting for a wave, avoid surfing in murky waters, and if you do surf with a buddy and embrace the crowd.  Tiger sharks are looking for the weak and injured animal that would not be in a group so crowds actually help to increase safety.  Sharks are incredibly important to the health of the ocean and reef ecosystems. Sharks don't see people as a food source and when they do bite swimmers or surfers it is the case of mistaken identity so let's help minimize confusion for them. mahalos for tuning in and helping sharks.  #helpsavesharks #surfers #coexist #sharks #tigershark editing and shot by my braddah @jarebutter

node.text: In this video I’m narrating and breaking down shark behavior and social dynamics between these 6 tiger sharks.  Riley is the dominate larger male right at the surface that then goes underneath Ocean giving her position as Alpha and the rest of the tigers follow him but this one little sand bar shark with attitude stills comes up to Ocean kinda challenging her.  Super interesting is that Riley is the only large male we have seen out here in 2 decades of diving and he has a very distinct looking dorsal.  Now we are seeing younger tiger sharks with this same genetic birth defect.  Riley could be related to these younger tiger sharks and maybe he is their father and maybe these large females seasonally come to this coast to either give birth or mate. Like male lions this could be Rilley’s pride.  We named Riley after a New Zealand shark scientist @thelifeofrileynz during one of visits with us @oneoceandiving @oneoceanresearch

node.text: Who is bigger? Me with my long freediving fins @cressi1946 and my @aquatech_imagingsolutions camera housing extended out or this massive tiger shark? Filming these amazingly misunderstood animals and trying to change their perceptions as monsters into important apex predators has lead me to many places in my life.  Two projects I’m proud to be involved in this years sharks week are @envoyfilm and the film “Fin” both are a must watch @discoveryplus Show shark week producers by watching these films that  you want to factual information and more shark conservation based shows. #sharkweek #sharkconservation #ApexPredatorNotMonsters #sharks #tigershark #fin #helpsavesharks #oneocean photo by my lava and beautiful wife @oceanramsey

We where lucky enough to see a single hammerhead shark today at @oneoceandiving but even just 10 years ago I could dive with 100s in the same  dive site.  Hammerheads like many others sharks are red listed as endangered species and need protection. 

Costa Rica ,  is home to a world heritage site for hammerheads and  other shark species that need help right now.  Please take a quick moment to speak up for sharks. 

(link in @onlyone bio @shawnheinrichs) to urge the Costa Rican President to immediately repeal his harmful executive decree and restore the Ministry of Environment’s authority to conserve and protect sharks.

#shark #sharkweek #hammerhead #marinelife #ocean #costarica #sharkweek2021 #turningthetide #helpsavesharks  amazing photo by @sametohoshi

We can’t  sanitize the ocean and if people want to swim or play in the ocean without inherent risk than go relax in a pool, the oceans ecosystem needs sharks and its biodiversity.  #rewild #savesharks #stopthesharknets  #oneocean #onechance #helpsavesharks

The #OneOceanSeries continues on IGTV & Youtube, watch others, and read the book and take the only course that this info builds on @OceanRamsey or via links in her bio on her website: OceanRamsey.Org

I’ve been working with sharks for well over 20 years around the world and I want people to have the amazing experience and connection felt when they get to go diving with them which is part of the reason @OcenaRamsey and I co-founded @Oneoceandiving and its many divisions because we know it will inspire conservation and respect is grown through a deeper understanding from knowledge shared.  

It is my hope that sharing this information will help people to be safer while enjoying time with sharks but we want to give a strong disclaimer that people should not attempt to reproduce scenes from this series, this is for emergency reference and awareness only.  The JAWSOME safety guides at @oneoceanDiving go through the most extensive and strenuous in-depth behavioral and applied training and if you’re ever going diving purposefully with sharks please be respectful and go with an extensively experienced professional guide who works with sharks in-water full time. 

@OneOceanDiving in unfortunatly losing one of its most amazing lady shark scientists because her husband is going to teach at a university on the mainland (congrats,) so we are hiring people with a deep passion for shark and marine conservation.  Must also already have a PADI divemaster certification or PADI freedive instructor cert, GRIT, and ideally with a marine science or related degree.   Apply by emailing the @OneoceanDiving office.

Disclaimer this sub-series is more than 4 parts, the 1st part of the series was released in 2 parts on @OceanRamsey’s IG and Part 3 will be on hers next.  We want to help people and sharks to coexist as safely and respectfully as possible and sometime that means giving them their space back and exiting the water, even if you’re extremely experienced working around them. We generally only start to share this information with professional shark safety diver guides once they’ve already been working with sharks on a daily basis for an extended period of time, only those who have the water skill required to quickly and efficiently move themselves in the water and adapt to a rapid approach and are trained to look in all directions continuously to see an approach or issue before it becomes a serious issue. As a photographer and videographer I want to get a stable shot but I won’t compromise safety to get that shot, it’s not worth disrespecting the sharks and risking their reputation so if I need to be stable then I have @Oceanramsey of one of the professional shark safety divers we’ve trained watch my back. 

I make deterring a large shark look easier than it is because I’ve done it a lot in many places around the world with many species and I’ve worked in the water daily for more than two decades specifically for water safety and mostly always focused around sharks. 

So, please be respectful of them and stay safe, don’t become complacent or assume every approach or shark species or location will be the same, it won’t. 

Special mahalo nui loa (thank you so much) to my love @OceanRamsey for filming me, being my safety, and demonstrating many of the techniques I talk about. Also special thank you to our amazing editor @Jarebutler for your incredible work. 

Learn more by taking @OceanRamsey’s online course, watching the rest of this free series, and check out Ocean’s book “What you should know about sharks” Link on my website JuanSharks.Com

Yesterday @oneoceandiving we were grateful to see “Queen Nikki Ali’i Nikole #SharkIDNikki Tiger Shark is alive and she came right up to our engines and ladder. 

In this video @oceanramsey gently deterred her away from the engines as much as possible along with our newest safety diver @hannahtuomistobell We are very happy and grateful to be visited by tiger sharks and get especially excited when it’s one of the ones we recognize from our @oneoceanresearch @oneoceansharks photo identification records. There are not that many tiger sharks and the larger ones like Nikki-Nik here tend to scare a lot of other sharks down deeper when they are around. 
We see an increase in Tiger sharks after whale season ends and the water warms up so it’s just the start of our Tiger Shark season now. 

Great group out with us and special thank you to return guest @karaedwards for coming back out and for part of this compilations clips 🤙🏽😍🦈😍🦈

node.text: Happy World sea turtle day! @oceanramsey taking a little walk with a few hawaiian green sea turtles after a reef clean up sponsored by @savetheseaturtlesinternational  By removing fishing line from coral reefs we are not only keeping the reef alive but this helps to minimize sea turtle entanglement while they are foraging for seaweed on the reef. Also @oceanramsey is wearing @oneoceanbikini which is a not for profit swim line made from recycled fishing line, all the proceeds go to @savetheseaturtlesinternational to help fund these sea life saving swims.  #savethereef #rewild #savetheseaturtles #savetheseaturtlesinternational #sealifesavingswim  #hawaiiangreenseaturtle #seaturtle #endangeredspecies #walkingwithturtles

node.text:
Sharks (Manō) are officially protected in Hawaii!!! Traditionally they always were but now, after years of pushing for further protection through the State legislation just yesterday (World Ocean Day) the governor of Hawaii signed the bill to give sharks protection from wasteful purposeful killing 🎉🎉🎉🎉🎉🎉🎉🎉🎉🎉🎉🎉🎉🎉
This measure was long overdue(you can see our efforts in @savingjawsmovie  from some years prior) but now incredible sharks, like ‘Grandma great white’ here and ‘Deep Blue’ and all the sharks I grew up with like Ali’i Nikole,
Roxy, and so many more will have the basic protection the deserve and need. 

Mahalo nui loa (thank you so much) to everyone who wrote in support of the bill being signed into law or wrote in testimony this year to help it along or any year prior, and to those who work daily to educate others about the importance, plight, and how to malama (care) for Manō (sharks.) 

Video shot by my amazing sharky wife @oceanramsey on her @gopro with @oneoceandiving 
That’s a rough tooth dolphin gracefully casually cruising around us 🐬🦈 Check out @oceanramsey last post to see how playful the dolphins were with big Grandma great white 💙
